(1)
5225 Church Ave., at the N.W. corner of East 53rd Street, showing the John Schenck House, built in 1822, demolished in 1927. It was owned by John Schenck until 1860, by his estate until 1873, by George Schenck until 1920 and by John Kolle in 1921.
March 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, showing the East 53rd Street side.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(3)
The same, from another angle.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster collection.

(1)
Church Ave., at the N.W. corner of East 53rd Street, showing the George Schenck house; also known as the "John Schenck homestead", which was razed in 1927, after almost a century in use. The family was one of the first to settle in Brooklyn.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, from another angle.

March 1923.

(1) Church Ave., at the N.W. corner of East 53rd Street. (Church Ave., is in the foreground, with the trolley tracks). The person who took the picture states it was the home of John Schenck. The maps of 1890, show it to be the estate of George Schenck, which contained five square blocks in this area. The house was razed in 1927.

September 1927.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing building in the process of demolition.

September 1927.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
